Web Skillup
Welcome to the Web Skillup program, presented by the Hyland Tech Outreach team!
Pre-Program Work
Please try to complete these items before the program begins:

Create a Replit account
Fill out the Pre-Program Assessment

Program Overview
This program is designed to cover essential web development concepts in HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. By the end of day two, all participants should have a solid grasp of the code in this project.
Given the short time frame, this will be a crash course. The hope is that each participant walks away feeling inspired and empowered to dive deeper into these topics and continue building their web development skills.
Lessons
The program consists of the following lessons:

Lesson 1: HTML
Lesson 2: CSS
Lesson 3: Hello JavaScript!
Lesson 4: Variables & Data
Lesson 5: Buttons & Functions
Lesson 6: Conditionals
Lesson 7: DOM Manipulation
Lesson 8: Arrays
Lesson 9: For Loops
Lesson 10: Objects

Additional Topics
In the event that all lessons have been completed before the end of the program, there are some additional topics to explore.
Resources
Click here for some helpful resources.

Lesson01Html/AboutMeCodeAlong.html.title: Code-Along
Lesson01Html/AboutMeCodeAlong.html.body:
Code-Along: About Me
Build a simple website about yourself, and learn about some HTML concepts along the way!
Getting Started
Start by forking the starter project. Make sure the index.html file is selected on the left to view the HTML code, and click the "Run" button. Notice how the code in the HTML creates the text on the website.
HTML Elements
Every individual thing you see on a website is an HTML element. Elements in HTML can be headers, blocks of text, pictures, videos, or anything else! Elements are the building blocks of HTML websites.
Tags
HTML elements are created with tags. Tags tell the website what type of element to display. Most HTML elements have an opening tag and a closing tag, with some content in between.
For example, the header at the top of the website is created with these components:

Opening Tag: 
Content: My Website
Closing Tag: 

Each tag is surrounded with these symbols:  and >. In HTML, it is common practice to refer to these as angle brackets. To break down the example further, the  opening tag is created with these parts:

Left Angle Bracket: 
Element Name: h1
Right Angle Bracket: >

For closing tags, there is also a slash (/) right before the element name, like this: .
Challenge: Update the Header
Unless your name is Carlito, this site is not accurate as of now! Update the code so that it has your name instead of Carlito.
Adding a Paragraph
Another common HTML element is the : the paragraph element. Make a new line, and add a  element that welcomes the user to your site. It could look something like this:
Hi, welcome to my site.

Adding a List of Hobbies
Next up, it's time to add a list of hobbies. To do this, it will be necessary to nest multiple elements together.
Nesting: Parent/Child Relationship
Nesting is one of the most important features of HTML; it allows some elements to contain other elements. For example, a list might look like this:

  Item One
  Item Two
  Item Three


Here, the  element is an unordered list. It contains the  elements - those are list items. This is what's called a parent/child relationship - the ul is the parent, and each li is a child. Typically, children are indented in the code.
Adding the List
Make a new line, and add an h2 header with text that says My Hobbies. Under that, create the , and add at least three  elements with three hobbies. It could end up looking like this:
My Hobbies

  Watching TV
  Watching Movies
  Listening to Music


Adding an Image
Next up, it's time to add an image. This is possible with the  element. This element is a little different; there is no closing tag, and an attribute is required to tell the element what picture to show. These are set inside of the opening tags. 
Make a new line, and create another h2 header that says A Cool Image. Under that, add the  element. Then, add the src attribute, and make it point to one of the images in the project. It might end up looking like this:
A Cool Image


Adding an Input
Another powerful element is the  element; this is how you allow users to provide your site with data. Like the  element, the  element does not have a closing tag, and it requires an attribute to determine the type. There are a ton of different types, but the most basic one is text.
Make a new line, and create another h2 header that says Form. Under that, add the  element. Then, add the type attribute, and make it text. Also, add the placeholder attribute, and make it say Please enter a message. It might end up looking like this:
Form


Organizing with  Elements
The div element is different in another way - it is specifically designed to contain other elements. It is used to help organize the page. It is a block-level element, which means its contents are displayed on their own line by default. Without CSS, they will not do much - but it is important to be able to recognize these elements and understand their purpose.
Add a  element to the page just for fun.
Conclusion
There are a ton more elements, and a lot more that HTML can do, but after this activity you should have a solid grasp of the basics. 
Final Code
The code in the index.html file might look something like this:

  
    About Carlito
    Hi, welcome to my site.

    My Hobbies
    
      Watching TV
      Watching Movies
      Listening to Music
    

    A Cool Image
    

    Form
    

    Just for fun

Lesson01Html/CustomElements.html.title: Custom Elements
Lesson01Html/CustomElements.html.body:
Custom Elements
Custom elements are an extremely powerful feature of HTML. They allow for the creation of custom tags that can encapsulate more functionality than the basic HTML elements do.
Background: The Shadow DOM
Some HTML elements are more than just basic blocks; they contain additional pieces and parts within them. For example, the  element can have a number of different internal elements depending on the type attribute:

Custom elements use the shadow DOM to pull together features and modularize them into standalone components.
Exploration
Fork the Example Project to check out some very basic custom elements in action!
Don't worry about looking at the script.js or style.css files yet; just try to use HTML to add more of the  and  elements! These aren't elements that come from the HTML spec; they are totally new and bespoke.
Being able to understand and use custom elements, even if you're not the one creating them, can be extremely helpful when working with frameworks.

Lesson02Css/Bootstrap.html.title: Bootstrap
Lesson02Css/Bootstrap.html.body:
Guided Activity: Bootstrap Magazine Website
Create a simple website for a magazine called Dirigible Digest. The website will contain articles related to dirigibles, and will be formatted using Bootstrap. A dirigible balloon, or airship, is a type of aerostat or lighter-than-air aircraft that can navigate through the air under its own power. For more information about dirigibles, refer to this article.
Setup
Start from this empty Repl, and then follow the instructions below.
HTML File

Open the index.html file, and add the basic tags: html, head, body
Within the  element, add the meta tag for viewport:   


Within the  element, add the link tag for the bootstrap stylesheet:   



CSS File

Create a new .css file named MagazineWebsite.css
Link the CSS file within the HTML file using a link tag

Code

    
        
        
        
    
    
    


Big Header
Bootstrap has built-in CSS class rulesets for headers called Jumbotrons. In order to use them, add some new HTML elements, and then add classes to them.
Basic HTML

Within the  element, add a div element
Within the  element, add an h1 element that says "Dirigible Digest"
Within the  element, add a p element that says "News and information related to dirigibles"

Open the file in a browser to see how it renders. It has the proper font, it needs to be centered and placed within a large header banner!
Jumbotron

Add a class attribute to the div element containing the header content
Set the value of the class attribute to "jumbotron"
Open the file in a browser to see the banner!
Back in the HTML file, add an additional class of "text-center" to the div
Use a space between the two classes to specify that the div has both classes


Open the file in a browser to see the text centered!

Adding CSS
To make the subtitle text appear italic, follow the steps below:

In the HTML file, add an id attribute to the p element, and set it to "subtitle"
In the CSS file, create a new ruleset for the p with an id of "subtitle"
Within the "subtitle" ruleset, create a new declaration setting font-style to italic
Open the file in a browser to see the italicized text!

Code
HTML

    Dirigible Digest
    News and information related to dirigibles


CSS
#subtitle {
    font-style: italic;
}

Article 1
Add an article about airships to the webpage. Ultimately, it should be laid out in a grid format, like a newspaper, and take up half of a row within a container.
Basic HTML

Within the  element, underneath the jumbotron , create another div
This div will represent the container for the rows


Within the container , create another div
This div will represent one row within the container


Within the row , create another div
This div will represent one article


Within the article , create an h3 header saying "Reprise of the airship"
Within the article , under the h3, create a p
Copy the following text into the p:   The U.S. is experiencing something of a blimp renaissance. There are more new airship designs coming off drawing boards than ever before and designers have ambitious plans for their use, provided they can rise above a number of technical hurdles--and the reservations of potential blimp operators...


Open the file in a browser to see how it renders. It has the proper content, but it needs some Bootstrap classes so that it appears within the grid!
Container / Row / Column

Add a class attribute to the container div, and set its value to "container"
Open the file in a browser, and notice the space is automatically added on the sides of the container
Add a class attribute to the row div, and set its value to "row"
Add a class attribute to the article div, and set its value to "col-md-6"
This will make the div take up 6 12ths (or one half) of the available row space


Open the file in a browser to see the article take up the proper amount of space

Code

    
        
            Reprise of the airship
            
                The U.S. is experiencing something of a blimp renaissance. There are more new airship designs coming off drawing boards than ever before and designers have ambitious plans for their use, provided they can rise above a number of technical hurdles--and the reservations of potential blimp operators...
            
        
    


Article 2
Add an additional article to the webpage. The second article should take up the other part of the first row.
HTML for Article 2

Within the row , underneath the existing article , add another div element
Add a class attribute to the new div element and set it to "col-md-6"
This way, the two article div elements will take up all the available space (6+6=12)


Within the new article , create an h3 header saying "Goodyear's blimp fleet complete"
Within the article , under the h3, create a p
Copy the following text into the p:   After years of planning and construction, Goodyear's fleet of high-technology Zeppelin airships is complete. The old blimp had two propeller engines that only pointed to the rear. But the new NTs have three engines that swivel in multiple directions, increasing maneuverability and control...


Adding CSS for All Articles
To make the article text appear dark grey, follow the steps below:

In the HTML file, add a class attribute to the p elements containing article text, and set the values to "article-text"
In the CSS file, create a new ruleset for the ps with a class of "article-text"
Within the "article-text" ruleset, create a new declaration setting color to darkgrey
Open the file in a browser to see the dark grey text!

Code
HTML

    Reprise of the airship
    
        The U.S. is experiencing something of a blimp renaissance. There are more new airship designs coming off drawing boards than ever before and designers have ambitious plans for their use, provided they can rise above a number of technical hurdles--and the reservations of potential blimp operators...
    


    Goodyear's blimp fleet complete
    
        After years of planning and construction, Goodyear's fleet of high-technology Zeppelin airships is complete. The old blimp had two propeller engines that only pointed to the rear. But the new NTs have three engines that swivel in multiple directions, increasing maneuverability and control...
    


CSS
.article-text {
    color: darkgrey;
}

Final Code
HTML

    
        
        
        
    
    
        
            Dirigible Digest
            News and information related to dirigibles
        
        
            
                
                    Reprise of the airship
                    
                        The U.S. is experiencing something of a blimp renaissance. There are more new airship designs coming off drawing boards than ever before and designers have ambitious plans for their use, provided they can rise above a number of technical hurdles--and the reservations of potential blimp operators...
                    
                
                
                    Goodyear's blimp fleet complete
                    
                        After years of planning and construction, Goodyear's fleet of high-technology Zeppelin airships is complete. The old blimp had two propeller engines that only pointed to the rear. But the new NTs have three engines that swivel in multiple directions, increasing maneuverability and control...
                    
                
            
        
    


CSS
#subtitle {
    font-style: italic;
}

.article-text {
    color: darkgrey;
}

Lesson02Css/CssPreprocessors.html.title: CSS Preprocessors
Lesson02Css/CssPreprocessors.html.body:
CSS Preprocessors
There are many CSS Preprocessors that make it much easier to work with CSS. They use a different (and often simpler) syntax, and compile it down to CSS. Learning to recognize and work with these different syntaxes can empower you to do a lot more with CSS.
Example: Sass
One of the most popular preprocessors is Sass. Read through the guide to familiarize yourself with some of the features.
Click here to play with a simple live example!
